            <p>1631 Chestnut St.<lb/>
                October 23rd 1894<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>In this morning&#39;s<lb/> Ledger under the heading of<lb/> &#34;Treatment of Animals&#34;<lb/> I notice your well timed remarks.<lb/>  As a member of the Board Penn<hi rend="sup">a</hi><lb/> Society to Protect Animals from<lb/> Cruelty I have looked carefully<lb/> into the matter of slaughtering<lb/> at our abattoir&#44; and also in<lb/> Chicago.  Besides this our Ag<hi rend="sup">t</hi><lb/> M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Fox whose duty it is to serve<lb/> at this point has led us both<lb/> to arrive at the conclusion<lb/> that our Forefathers methods<lb/> according to the Jewish rites<lb/> was and is the most humane<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>and healthful. <del>method</del>&#45;&#45;The<lb/> knocking in the head with an<lb/> iron instrument is uncertain<lb/> and frequently fails to effect<lb/> its purpose until several blows<lb/> are given.  The animal<lb/> falls and upon opening it<lb/> coagulated clots of blood are<lb/> found in its body.  With the<lb/> knife a painless death is sure&#44;<lb/> and no clots are found in the<lb/> body.  Much discussion has<lb/> arisen on this subject&#44; and I<lb/> think candour compels an<lb/> acknowledgment in our favor&#45;<lb/> from all <hi rend="underline">those Societies</hi> engaged<lb/> in this Humanitarian work.<lb/></p>
            <p>With kindest regards Truly&#45;<lb/> Lucien Moss.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
